{"title_page": "Mir Shams-ud-Din Araqi", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Aga Mir Syed Mohammad Baqir Mosavi}}\n\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| background     = #006000\n| name           = Mir Shams-ud-Din Araqi \n| image          =\n| religion       = [[Shia Islam]], [[Jaffari]]\n| alias          = [[Mir Syed Mohammad Moosavi Isfahani]]\n| location       = [[Srinagar]], [[Kashmir]]\n| Title          = \u0645\u06cc\u0631 \u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u06cc\n| Period         =1460-1515 \n| Predecessor    = Aga Mir Syed Ibrahim Mosavi Isfahani\n| Successor      =  \n| ordination     =\n| post           = [[Allamah|Allama]], [[Cleric]]\n| birth_date  = 1440 AD, (13 Rajab 861 AH)\n| birth_place = [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date  = 1515 AD (01 Rabiul Awwal 936 AH)\n| death_place = [[Chadoora]], [[Budgam]],\n [[Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| website        = {{URL|Raheislam.org}}\n}}\n{{Noorbakshi Islam}}\n[[File:mirshamsuddinaraqi.jpg|thumb|Grave of Mir Shahms-ud-Din Araqi]]\n'''Mir Syed Mohammed Isfahani''' alias '''Mir Shams-ud-din Muhammad Iraqi''' (1440&ndash;1515) ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u06cc\u0631 \u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u06cc }}}}) was known for having introduced the tenets held by  [[Noorbakshi]],<ref name=\"Bakshi1997\">{{cite book|author=Shiri Ram Bakshi|title=Kashmir: Valley and Its Culture|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_U1LEY1yWmagC|year=1997|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-85431-97-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_U1LEY1yWmagC/page/n16 231]}}</ref> the order of the Twelver Shia [[Sufis]] in [[Kashmir]] who influenced the social fabric of the valley.\n\nMir Shams ud-Din first came from [[Arak, Iran|Araq]] a city in [[Iran]] via [[Gilgit]] [[Skardu]] Road to [[Ladakh]] and [[Kashmir]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|title=\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u0634\u06cc\u0639\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0634\u0645\u06cc\u0631|trans-title=History of the Shiites of Kashmir|language=}}</ref> as a political envoy of [[Hassan Shah]] and then became an independent religious missionary. He is considered founder of [[Shia Islam]] in [[Gilgit]], [[Ladakh]], [[Kashmir]] and its adjoining areas.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yatoo |first1=Altaf Hussain |title=The Islamization of Kashmir: A Study of MuslimMissionaries |date=2012 |publisher=Gulshan Books |location=Kashmir, India |isbn=9788183391467}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\" /> After arriving in [[Srinagar]], he established his [[Khanqah]] in the suburbs, now known as Zaddibal. His [[Khanqah]] produced many of the future military leaders of Kashmir. He was best known for influencing the nobles of the Chak clan to embrace the Nurbakshi faith as well as [[Shia Islam]]. Mir Sham ud-Din Iraqi translated the book ''Fiqh-i-Ahwat'' (book of jurisprudence), which was written in Arabic by his teacher ''Syed Muhammad Nurbaksh.''{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\nHe was martyred in 1515 A.D.and was buried at Zaddibal [[Srinagar]].<ref name=\"auto\" /> Later his funeral was shifted to [[Chadoora]] due to unforeseen conditions. Presently he is buried at the Shrine of [[Chadoora]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nHe is a descendant of [[Musa al-Kazim]].\n[[File:family_tree_of_msa.jpg|thumb|Family tree of Mir Shams-ud-din Araqi]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iranian Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:1484 births]]\n[[Category:1526 deaths]]\n[[Category:History of Kashmir]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Aga Mir Syed Mohammad Baqir Mosavi}}\n\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| background     = #006000\n| name           = Mir Shams-ud-Din Araqi \n| image          =\n| religion       = [[Shia Islam]], [[Jaffari]]\n| alias          = [[Mir Syed Mohammad Moosavi Isfahani]]\n| location       = [[Srinagar]], [[Kashmir]]\n| Title          = \u0645\u06cc\u0631 \u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u06cc\n| Period         =1460-1515 \n| Predecessor    = Aga Mir Syed Ibrahim Mosavi Isfahani\n| Successor      =  \n| ordination     =\n| post           = [[Allamah|Allama]], [[Cleric]]\n| birth_date  = 1440 AD, (13 Rajab 861 AH)\n| birth_place = [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date  = 1515 AD (01 Rabiul Awwal 936 AH)\n| death_place = [[Chadoora]], [[Budgam]],\n [[Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| website        = {{URL|Raheislam.org}}\n}}\n{{Noorbakshi Islam}}\n[[File:mirshamsuddinaraqi.jpg|thumb|Grave of Mir Shahms-ud-Din Araqi]]\n'''Mir Syed Mohammed Isfahani''' alias '''Mir Shams-ud-din Muhammad Iraqi''' (1440&ndash;1515) ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0645\u06cc\u0631 \u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u0646 \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u06cc }}}}) was known for having introduced the tenets held by  [[Noorbakshi]],<ref name=\"Bakshi1997\">{{cite book|author=Shiri Ram Bakshi|title=Kashmir: Valley and Its Culture|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_U1LEY1yWmagC|year=1997|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-85431-97-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_U1LEY1yWmagC/page/n16 231]}}</ref> the order of the Twelver Shia [[Sufis]] in [[Kashmir]] who influenced the social fabric of the valley.\n\nMir Shams ud-Din first came from [[Arak, Iran|Araq]] a city in [[Iran]] via [[Gilgit]] [[Skardu]] Road to [[Ladakh]] and [[Kashmir]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|title=\u062a\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u0634\u06cc\u0639\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0634\u0645\u06cc\u0631|trans-title=History of the Shiites of Kashmir|language=}}</ref> as a political envoy of [[Hassan Shah]] and then became an independent religious missionary. He is considered founder of [[Shia Islam]] in [[Gilgit]], [[Ladakh]], [[Kashmir]] and its adjoining areas.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yatoo |first1=Altaf Hussain |title=The Islamization of Kashmir: A Study of MuslimMissionaries |date=2012 |publisher=Gulshan Books |location=Kashmir, India |isbn=9788183391467}}</ref> <ref name=\"auto\"/> After arriving in [[Srinagar]], he established his [[Khanqah]] in the suburbs, now known as Zaddibal. His [[Khanqah]] produced many of the future military leaders of Kashmir. He was best known for influencing the nobles of the Chak clan to embrace the Nurbakshi faith as well as [[Shia Islam]]. Mir Sham ud-Din Iraqi translated the book ''Fiqh-i-Ahwat'' (book of jurisprudence), which was written in Arabic by his teacher ''Syed Muhammad Nurbaksh.''{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\nHe was martyred in 1515 A.D.and was buried at Zaddibal [[Srinagar]]. <ref name=\"auto\"/> Later his funeral was shifted to [[Chadoora]] due to unforeseen conditions. Presently he is buried at the Shrine of [[Chadoora]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nHe is a descendant of [[Musa al-Kazim]].\n[[File:family_tree_of_msa.jpg|thumb|Family tree of Mir Shams-ud-din Araqi]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iranian Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:1484 births]]\n[[Category:1526 deaths]]\n[[Category:History of Kashmir]]\n", "name_user": "SlackingViceroy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed some spacing issues.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mir_Shams-ud-Din_Araqi"}
